In contrast with Pht and Nar, the MIC value of the antibiotic Cip was not modified by the application of either PAβN or NMP in Pb 1692 (
Table 1
), suggesting that the inhibitors did not impair Cip efflux from the cell. This may suggest that the inhibitors block the passage of Nar or Pht through the efflux pathway to a higher degree than the passage of the antibiotic. In drug resistant E. coli, the pump preferentially removes PAβN, while the antibiotic accumulates in the cell until the concentration is sufficient to impair the target’s activity. This mode of action allows in most cases to sensitize the bacteria, or completely reverse resistance to a given compound (Bolla et al., 2011).

